3. Which animal groups are represented in the data? Make a plot that shows the number in each class.

ggplot(data=homerange, mapping=aes(x=class))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(fill=class))+
  labs(title="Numbers in each animal group")

Answer: Mammalia is most represented.

4. Are there more carnivores or herbivores represented in the data? Make a plot that shows the number in each trophic guild.

  ggplot(data=homerange, mapping=aes(x=trophic.guild))+
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(fill=trophic.guild))+
  labs(title="Numbers in carnivores or herbivores")

Answer: More carnivores represented in the data 5. Which herbivorous mammals have homeranges greater than 1,000,000 m? Show only the common name, order, mean homerange size, and mean body mass. Arrange the data in descending order by homerange size and show only the top 10 species.

homerange %>% 
  select(common.name, order, mean.hra.m2, mean.mass.g) %>% 
  filter(mean.hra.m2>=1000000) %>% 
  slice_max(mean.hra.m2, n = 10)

6. Which two species have the largest and smallest homerange sizes?

homerange %>% 
  select(species, mean.hra.m2) %>% 
  slice_max(mean.hra.m2, n=1)
##    species mean.hra.m2
## 1 tarandus  3550830977
homerange %>% 
  select(species, mean.hra.m2) %>% 
  slice_min(mean.hra.m2, n=1)
##    species mean.hra.m2
## 1 hipoliti        0.03

Answer: tarandus have the largest homerange size, while hipoliti have the smallest homerange size 7. Which carnivorous mammals have the largest homeranges?

Answer: Jubatus of carnivorous mammals have the largest homeranges

8. Is there a relationship between body mass and homerange size? Make a scatterplot to show this relationship. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

ggplot(data = homerange, mapping = aes(x=mean.mass.g, y=mean.hra.m2))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color=trophic.guild))+
  geom_smooth(method = lm,se=T)+
    scale_x_log10()+
  scale_y_log10()+
   labs(title = "Body Mass in log10 (g) vs. Homerange Size in log10 (m^2)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Answer: there is a positive relationship between body mass and home range size

9. Use filter to extract the data for only birds and mammals. Then make a plot that compares the homerange sizes of these two groups. Be sure to include appropriate labels and a title.

homerange %>% 
  select(taxon, mean.hra.m2)%>% 
  filter(taxon== "birds" | taxon== "mammals")%>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = taxon, y=mean.hra.m2))+
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(fill=taxon))+
    scale_y_log10()+
  labs(title="Home Range Size in log10 (m^2) by birds and mammals")
